tem called Reinforcement Learning by Human Feedback, and “OpenAI” has been very closed about exactly how that really works. And how it performs in practice depends on what training data it is trained on (this is what the Kenyans were creating). And, guess what, “Open” AI isn’t open about those data, either.</p><p>In fact the whole thing is like an alien life form. Three decades as a professional cognitive psychologist, working with adults and children, never prepared me for this kind of insanity:</p><a href="https://twitter.com/goodside/status/1623557794996551680?s=46&amp;t=0mmOU6M3Ma2xSolmlel9Jw" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/-FHvWusRVCOn0eN8OLWClwZTPWkZPBWRokiI8sQr83E=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvdHdpdHRlcl9uYW1lL3dfOTYvZ29vZHNpZGUuanBn" alt="Twitter avatar for @goodside" loading="lazy"/>Riley Goodside @goodside&#34;SolidGoldMagikarp&#34;: Prompting GPT-3 / ChatGPT to repeat any of several hundred anomalous tokens elicits bizarre generations — described by researchers as variously &#34;evasive,&#34; &#34;hallucinatory,&#34; &#34;insulting,&#34; &#34;ominously humorous,&#34; and &#34;religiously themed.&#34;
