o this essay, working title “Mayim Bialek, Large Language Models, and the Future of the Internet: What Google Should Really Be Worried About“, that will illustrate what rings of fake websites look like, what their economics are,  and why likely increase in them could matter so much.</p><p><em><strong><a href="http://garymarcus.com" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Gary Marcus</a> </strong>(@garymarcus),<strong> </strong>scientist, bestselling author, and entrepreneur, is a skeptic about current AI but genuinely wants to see the best AI possible for the world—and still holds a tiny bit of optimism. Sign up to his Substack (free!), and <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/01/06/opinion/ezra-klein-podcast-gary-marcus.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">listen to him on Ezra Klein</a>. His most recent book, co-authored with Ernest Davis,<a href="http://rebooting.ai/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"> Rebooting AI</a>, is one of Forbes’s 7 Must Read Books in AI. </em></p><p></p>